  <main>
    <div class="container-fluid">
      <div class="homepage-description js-challenge">
        <!-- Challenge name -->
        <h1 class="text-center">limitedAlert</h1>
        <!-- Problem statement -->
        <div class="problem-statement px-5">
          <p>
            Create a function
            <code>limitedAlert()</code> which shows an alert when it's called, but only up to 3 calls.
          </p>
          <p>Examples:</p>
          <pre>
    limitedAlert('something went wrong') // show alert
    limitedAlert('something went wrong') // show alert
    limitedAlert('something went wrong') // show alert
    limitedAlert('something went wrong') // NO MORE ALERTS</pre>
        </div>
        <!-- Gist -->
        <div class="gist">
          <script src="https://gist.github.com/AlvinKang/72d67069a5fd6e7bd7b02b012a4c8bda.js"></script>
        </div>
        <!-- Questions -->
        <div class="follow-up px-5">
          <div class="question">
            <h3>Can you do it without exposing a global variable? Why would that be important?</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="response">
            <p>Yes, since even functions are objects in JavaScript, I can make a property called
              <code>calledTimes</code> that gets incremented every time the function is called. Not polluting the global namespace in JavaScript
              is important because other js script files share the global namespace. So for instance, if
              <code>limitedAlert()</code> is in
              <code>scriptA.js</code> and I used a global variable
              <code>count</code>, that variable can be accessed and overwritten in another
              <code>scriptB.js</code>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <!-- Test link -->
        <div class="test-link text-right px-5">
          <img src="/glyphicons/png/glyphicons-153-check.png" />
          <a href="/tests">Go to tests</a>
        </div>
      </div>
